data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsException<T>`, which is more precise — it scopes the assertion to the exact line expected to throw:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
}
```

**Why?** `[ExpectedException]` catches exceptions from *any* line in the test (including Arrange), masking bugs. `Assert.ThrowsException` targets only the specific call.

**MSTest v4+** renames it to `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`. You can also capture the exception to assert on its message:

```csharp
var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
    () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));
Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
```
